3. RESTRICTIONS ON FORKS AND DERIVATIVE WORKS

   The right to create a Fork in Section 2(c) is granted under the following STRICT CONDITIONS:

   a) The Fork must be created on the same code-hosting platform as the primary repository (e.g., GitHub, GitLab) to facilitate the Pull Request mechanism.
   b) The Fork must be DESTROYED (i.e., the repository must be deleted) upon the earliest of:
        i) The rejection or closure of the associated Pull Request without merger.
        ii) The successful merger of the Pull Request into the primary repository.
        iii) Six (6) months after the creation of the Fork, if no Pull Request has been submitted.
   c) You are EXPRESSLY PROHIBITED from:
        i) Using the Fork or any code within it for any purpose other than developing a contribution for the primary repository.
        ii) Distributing, publishing, sublicensing, selling, or otherwise transferring the Fork or any code from it.
        iii) Using the Fork or any code from it for any commercial purpose.
        iv) Maintaining the Fork as a public, long-term derivative work. The Fork is a temporary, private workspace for contribution.

